+{"id":"br-r40-c2-01","title":"REVIEW: [HIGH] bfs_beam_edges filtered frontier globally instead of locally + is_kl_connected / kl_connected_subgraph used wrong algorithm","description":"Two behavioural defects in the traversal / hybrid module:

1. bfs_beam_edges: fnx sorted the whole frontier by value and kept the top-width, then visited ALL neighbours of those. nx's algorithm is a LOCAL beam — at each visited node it enqueues only the top-width neighbours (by value descending). On karate_club_graph with degree-valued `value` and width=3, fnx emitted 32 edges, nx emitted 7. Fixed by rewriting over generic_bfs_edges with a per-node successor function returning `sorted(G.neighbors(v), key=value, reverse=True)[:width]`, matching nx exactly (7 edges, identical order).

2. is_kl_connected / kl_connected_subgraph: fnx's implementation tested node-cut properties via combinations over node subsets, which has nothing to do with nx's definition — nx defines (k, l)-local connectivity per EDGE: for each (u, v) there must be l edge-disjoint paths. On karate_club_graph: fnx.is_kl_connected(G, 2, 1) returned False, nx returned True. And fnx.kl_connected_subgraph kept dropping nodes instead of pruning edges, collapsing karate to 2 nodes vs nx's 34. Rewrote both to mirror nx's edge-iteration + edge-disjoint-path algorithm (with optional low_memory neighbourhood restriction).","status":"closed","priority":2,"issue_type":"bug","created_at":"2026-04-24T00:00:00Z","updated_at":"2026-04-24T00:00:00Z","close_reason":"Fixed. bfs_beam_edges exact-matches nx; is_kl_connected matches nx on karate/path/K4 across several (k,l); kl_connected_subgraph matches nx on karate for (2,1) and (3,2); same_as_graph bit also matches."}
